The HD 16141 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 16141 is a star with 1.11 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.48 times its radius. It is located 123.24 light years away from the solar system.

HD 16141 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 16141 system


HD 16141 b

HD 16141 b was discovered by the W. M. Keck Observatory observatory, in 2000-06, using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 0.36 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 16141 b is 82.680 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 16141 b is 10.900 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 16141 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
